x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: Error from the graphic bars are an
estimate of the possible systematic errors; the primary
source being the subtraction of the contribution from
the oxygen contaminant.
No explanation of relative units is given.
The scintillation counter consisted of a
CsI(Tl) crystal 1 mm thick mounted on a Dumont 6291
photomultiplier tube was used.
The beryllium target was a foil 1 mil thick and 1.0625
in. in diameter. It showed evidence of oxygen
contamination in addition to the single stable isotope
of beryllium.
Fig.5(b)

x4freetext: No explanation of relative units is given.
The scintillation counter consisted of a
CsI(Tl) crystal 1 mm thick mounted on a Dumont 6291
photomultiplier tube was used.
The boron targets were prepared from enriched isotopes
which were in the form of a "metallic" powder. For the
B10 target, a water suspension of the powder was
allowed to settle onto a 1/4-mil polyethylene foil,
leaving a fairly uniform target with a surface density
of ~3 mg/cm2.
Fig.6(a)

x4freetext: No explanation of relative units is given.
A NaI(Tl) crystal 2 mm thick was used.
The boron targets were prepared from enriched isotopes
which were in the form of a "metallic" powder. A
suspension of the B11 powder in polystyrene Q-dope
thinner was prepared and a very small amount of
polystyrene Q-dope was added to the suspension to serve
as a binder. The suspension was then allowed to settle
out onto the nickel foil as the liquid evaporated,
leaving a uniform target 6 mg/cm2 thick.
Fig.7
